Look forward to working with you again next week. https://ttcsppjuly.peatix.com/view  Origin and basics of MBTI  Myers-Briggs theory is an adaptation of the theory of psychological types produced by Carl Gustav Jung. It is based on 16 personality types, which Jung viewed as stereotypes (Jung 1921, p. 405). They act as useful reference points to understand your unique personality (Jung 1957, p. 304). At the heart of Myers Briggs theory are four preferences. Do you prefer to deal with: People and things (Extraversion or "E"), or ideas and information (Introversion or "I").  Facts and reality (Sensing or "S"), or possibilities and potential (Intuition or "N").  Logic and truth (Thinking or "T"), or values and relationships (Feeling or "F").  A lifestyle that is well-structured (Judgment or "J"), or one that goes with the flow (Perception or "P").   Extraversion and Introversion - The first pair of styles is concerned with the direction of your energy. If you prefer to direct your energy to deal with people, things, situations, or "the outer world", then your preference is for Extraversion. If you prefer to direct your energy to deal with ideas, information, explanations or beliefs, or "the inner world", then your preference is for Introversion.  Sensing and Intuition - The second pair concerns the type of information/things that you process. If you prefer to deal with facts, what you know, to have clarity, or to describe what you see, then your preference is for Sensing. If you prefer to deal with ideas, look into the unknown, to generate new possibilities or to anticipate what isn't obvious, then your preference is for Intuition. The letter N is used for intuition because I has already been allocated to Introversion. Thinking and Feeling - The third pair reflects your style of decision-making. If you prefer to decide on the basis of objective logic, using an analytic and detached approach, then your preference is for Thinking. If you prefer to decide using values - i.e. on the basis of what or who you believe is important - then your preference is for Feeling. Judgment and Perception - The final pair describes the type of lifestyle you adopt. If you prefer your life to be planned and well-structured then your preference is for Judging. This is not to be confused with 'Judgmental', which is quite different. If you prefer to go with the flow, to maintain flexibility and respond to things as they arise, then your preference is for Perception.  https://www.teamtechnology.co.uk/tt/t-articl/mb-simpl.htm

CONVERSATION TITLE: An Immersive Teacher Residency in MA
CONTENT:
Hi Sajiah,


Are you ready to empower students to build skills for lifetime success?


With Lesley University’s Teacher Residency Master of Education (M.Ed.) programs, you’ll gain the advanced strategies you need to be an effective, resilient educator in just over a year. You'll work full time in an independent or public school while completing graduate education courses with Lesley, a nationally-recognized leader in teacher preparation.


Lesley teachers are the #1 choice of Massachusetts employers, who know they’re hiring professional, highly skilled educators who are prepared to make a difference in the classroom on day one.


The Teacher Residency program delivery model offers:


  • A year-long immersive teaching residency at a leading school in Greater Boston or New England
  • A Master of Education (M.Ed.) and an Initial Teaching License in a range of grade levels and subjects, including Early Childhood through Middle School Education, English as a Second Language (ESL), and Inclusive Special Education
  • An affordable tuition rate from New England’s leader in teacher preparation
  • Immense support from Lesley faculty throughout the entire program 


Teacher Residency M.Ed. programs begin once a year and the next start date is June 2022. 


Learn more about joining our Summer Teacher Residency M.Ed. programs and becoming a licensed educator. 


Sign up to talk to me about this opportunity. I can help you get started.


Sincerely,


Debbie Mosher 

Regional Director

Lesley University
